\begin_layout Section*
Regressions on Income and Expenditure Survey
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kaus considers a black-dummy and coloured-dummy in regression of visible
 consumption against demographic, time, permanent income and household character
isitcs.
 Starting with no controls(I)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
lm(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (with black-dummy and coloured-dummy), the coefficients for coloured and
 black are negative (i.e.
 black and coloured social groups spend less on visible consumption than
 the white population).
 However, these coefficients flip signs after adding income controls(II)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
lm(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lninc) 
\family default
- where lninc is log(income_household_head).
 Notice that only log of income level is found significant when used along
 side with income-level-cubic and income level.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficients for black and coloured groups are even higher when expenditure
 is added(III)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
lm(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lninc+lnpinc) 
\family default
- where lnpinc is log of total expenditure (which itself is a proxy for
 permanent income)
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The endogeneity of total expenditure requires instrumentation - Kaus uses
 instruments suggested by Charles, Roussanov and Hurst - including positive-inco
me-dummy, cube-of-income-level, dummies for under-secondary-education, secondary
-eduation and degree-education.
 Kaus then performs two 2SLS regressions - one with income controls and
 total-expenditure as control variables
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
ivreg(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lninc+ lnpinc | .
 - lnpinc + cbinc + lsecd + secd + degree)
\family default
 - where lsecd,secd and degree are education dummies and cbinc is income-level-c
ubic.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the other with education-dummies as control variables (while still
 using instruments)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
ivreg(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lnpinc +lsecd | .
 - lnpinc + cbinc+lninc +incpsv
\family default
) 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The instrumentation thus performed (Specification IV in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "resresults-1"

\end_inset

) results in lower coefficients for the black and coloured dummies for both
 regressions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When demographic params are added(VI), the coefficients are further lowered
 (without changing 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 a lot) - for both types of regressions 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First: 
\family typewriter
ivreg(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lninc+ lnpinc + age+ n_members +
 area_type| .
 - lnpinc + cbinc + lsecd + secd + degree) 
\family default
Second: 
\family typewriter
ivreg(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lnpinc +lsecd + age + n_members
 + area_type | .
 - lnpinc + cbinc+lninc +incpsv)
\family default
 - where n_members is the number of members in the household and area_type
 is urban/rural factor
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of the above interpretations match with those reported in Kaus's paper.
 The regression V from the paper is ommitted for 1995 - as the data on visible
 consumption from 2005/2010 wasn't available from datafirst to be included
 in the regression with year-dummies.
 The data from 2000 - is of poor quality (as explained by Kaus) and does
 not have enough household characteristic fields for applying an analysis
 in the Kaus's paper - and was thus discarded altogether.
 For 2005/2010, the only field amongst all in the visible category available
 to us - is the number-of-cars-owned by the household ( rather than cars
 purchased in the surveyed period).
 Hardly meant to conclusive on visible consumption, if owned cars were still
 to be considered the proxy for visible consumption, a reversal of signs
 after adding of income-controls is not observed.
 Other results equivalent to 1995 result-set are summarized in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "resresults-2"

\end_inset

 (Notice that specification V is possible when more than an year is available
 for analysis).
 What the results suggest is only that unlike visible consumption, the ownership
 of cars is very much influenced by permanent income (and other wealth character
istics accounting for lower ownership of cars for the black and coloured
 groups).
\end_layout

