\begin_layout Section*
Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first-change of sign when income controls are added implies that after
 accounting for income of household head, the coloured and black groups
 spend more on visible consumption.
 Total expenditure is not a perfect proxy of permanent income - which justifies
 instrumentation.
 After resolving these endogeneity concerns - with a regression of visible
 expenditure as dependent variable and total-expenditure as one of the control
 variables - the signs are revised - although 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 does not change a lot.
 Adding demographic controls to the 2SLS regression - shows significance
 of age, urban/rural area and family size - but coefficients are still not
 lowered significantly.
 This confirms that coloured and black social groups spend a rather disprportion
ate amount on visible consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second claim that the paper is interested in is testing whether the
 rise in average group income reduces the visible consumption.
 The regression considers average-incomes of particular provinces for every
 group (black/white/coloured).
 This regression shows the effect more on black-social-group than the white-soci
al-group - a difference that author argues points out alternate ways of
 signaling for white-social-group relative to black-social-group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
AER toolbox ivreg notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regressors and instruments in implementaiton of ivreg in R-toolbox AER are
 specified in a formula with two parts on the right-hand side.
 The specification - used in this note - can be either of the form - 
\family typewriter
y ~ ex + en | ex + in 
\family default
or as 
\family typewriter
y ~ ex + en | .
 - en +in 
\family default
(where 
\family typewriter
ex
\family default
 is the set of exogenous variables, 
\family typewriter
en
\family default
 is the set of endogenous variables and 
\family typewriter
in 
\family default
the set of instruments) .
 The latter is the notation used throughout in this note.
\end_layout

